  "text_preview": "\"number\" ASL American Sign Language ASL University ► Numbers: 1,000 and up Numbers 1-10 / 11-20 / 21-30 / 31-40 / 100-900 / 1000 and up / Fractions 987,654,321 The sign \"thousand\" is done in context as part of a specific number or as part of the concept \"thousands.\" If you don't do the \"number prefix\" this sign looks a lot like the sign for \"AGAIN.\" 1,000: \"one thousand\" or \"a thousand\" Here is another view of 1,000: To sign the thousands, just combine the first part of the number with the bent hand touching the left palm. For example, 2,000 starts with a \"2\" and then changes into a bent hand and touches the left palm. 2,000: 2,397: See an animated example of the number 2397 ► (258 KB) See an animated example of the number 2397 (258 KB) ONE-MILLION: \"Thousands\" or \"Millions\" When you want "
